Broadcasting antenna in <a href="/wiki/Stuttgart" title="Stuttgart">Stuttgart</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Broadcasting</b> is the <a href="/wiki/Distribution_(business)" title="Distribution (business)">distribution</a> of <a href="/wiki/Sound" title="Sound">audio</a> and <a href="/wiki/Video" title="Video">video</a> content to a dispersed <a href="/wiki/Audience" title="Audience">audience</a> via any audio or visual <a href="/wiki/Medium_(communication)" title="Medium (communication)" class="mw-redirect">mass communications medium</a>, but usually one using <a href="/wiki/Electromagnetic_radiation" title="Electromagnetic radiation">electromagnetic radiation</a> (<a href="/wiki/Radio_wave" title="Radio wave" class="mw-redirect">radio waves</a>). The receiving parties may include the general public or a relatively large subset thereof. Broadcasting has been used for purposes of private recreation, <a href="/wiki/Non-commercial" title="Non-commercial">non-commercial</a> exchange of messages, experimentation, self-training, and emergency communication such as <a href="/wiki/Amateur_radio" title="Amateur radio">amateur (ham) radio</a> and <a href="/wiki/Amateur_television" title="Amateur television">amateur television</a> (ATV) in addition to commercial purposes like popular radio or TV stations with advertisements.</p>
